 explores the work and tensions involved in the production and valuation of durability to outline a new agenda for more sustainable economies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aCircular Economy. 4aDurable Goods. 4aEconomic Sociology. 4aEconomy. 4aObsolescence. 4aRepair. 4aSociology of Technology. 4aSociology of Work and Industry. 4aSociology. 4aSustainability. 4aTechnology. 4aWork. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aCircular Economy.  aDurable Goods.  aEconomic Sociology.  aEconomy.  aObsolescence.  aRepair.  aSociology of Technology.  aSociology of Work and Industry.  aSociology.  aSustainability.  aTechnology.  aWork.1 aDalhammar, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrick, Vivian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHielscher, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHipp, Tamina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHofmann, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHofmann, Florian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJaeger-Erben, Melanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaeger-Erben, Melanie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLepawsky, Josh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuth Richter, Jessika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaitre-Ekern, Eléonore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb